            "last_activity_date": 1503220314,
            "creation_date": 1503204086,
            "body": "<p>You should not rely on <code>_id<\/code> column of the database to uniquely identify a row in the table, like if you have 3 rows and the table will have <code>_id<\/code> as 0, 1, 2. That is not the case. <\/p>\n\n<p>That value <code>_id<\/code> column gets incremented irrespective of the total number of rows in your table. For example, if you have 3 rows initially, you might have <code>_id<\/code> as 0, 1, 2. Then If you delete the first two rows and add the same 2 rows again, you will have 2, 3, 4 as <code>_id<\/code>. <\/p>\n\n<p>So to uniquely identify a row in your table, you should define your own unique id (like UUID) in a separate column, that does not change for row deletion and addition. <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 45778518,
            "question_id": 45777979,
            "last_edit_date": 1503220314
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/qGBvY.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 10282306,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 7586922,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/7586922/the-abstract-lightbulb",
                "reputation": 3,
